<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Analysis): White Paper promises long-overdue
reform - Change in Presentation of Tax and Spending Proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PLENDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUDGET DAY may be one of the great theatrical events in the British
political calendar, but it has precious little to do with anything that
resembles a proper budget. In effect, there are two half-budgets, with
public spending decisions being announced in the Autumn Statement, while the
means of financing those expenditures remains a carefully kept secret until
the Budget in the following year. The chancellor of the day then sows joy
and despair in equal measure as he pulls rabbits out of his hat and unveils
complex tax measures that have not been subjected to scrutiny in open
debate.
By deciding to bring together the government's tax and spending proposals on
one date in December, Mr Lamont has struck a long overdue blow for more
rational economic policy making. It may not set the C1 and C2 socio-economic
groups alight in Tory marginal constituencies, but it was certainly
theatrical, in the sense that the shadow chancellor has been upstaged. Mr
John Smith had been a cogent advocate of budgetary reform. On this, as on
income tax, he has seen his clothes deftly purloined by the chancellor.
The case for reform has long been accepted. Sir Geoffrey Howe pinned his
colours to the mast in opposition in 1977, but then failed to deliver after
he became chancellor in 1979. A report in 1980 by Lord Armstrong of
Sanderstead for the Institute For Fiscal Studies firmly attacked the
separation of tax and spending decisions and was echoed in a further report
by the Treasury and Civil Service Committee in 1982. But it probably took Mr
Smith's advocacy to bring about this belated enthusiasm for change; and
while the initiative may now have been lost to Mr Lamont, the shadow
chancellor may yet have the last laugh if the first genuine budget, planned
for December 1993, is delivered under Labour.
The case against the present budgetary process is that it is confusing and
incoherent. When revenue and expenditure statements are finally brought
together in the Financial Statement and Budget Report that accompanies the
annual budget, attention inevitably fixes on the tax proposals, since the
spending decisions have been in the public domain for months. Perceptions
are thus distorted; and in the traditional battle on the Finance Bill
Standing committee, ministers frequently fail to give a proper account of
the proposed legislation.
The White Paper that accompanied yesterday's Budget argued that a unified
budget would enable ministers to make better judgments about the merits of
public spending proposals in the light of the overall fiscal position and
the implications for taxation. The components of the government's fiscal
policy will be more clearly presented for parliamentary and public debate.
Few would disagree with this analysis. But there are snags. These include
the delay that will now take place in the publication of departmental
spending plans and the fact that taxation decisions will be taken well
before the start of the new financial year. There will also be a host of
legal and technical obstacles, not least the implication for computer
systems at the Inland Revenue and in industry of merging the two separate
annual coding exercises that now take place for Pay As You Earn purposes.
The government has finally conceded that these problems are outweighed by
the advantages. But it remains to be seen just how open a budgetary process
will emerge in due course. The White Paper says that income tax rates and
allowances will take effect, as they do now, from the start of the tax year.
But there will also be surprises, where there is a risk that taxpayers will
seek to forestall changes to minimise their liability.
That said, the White Paper also emphasises that one of the advantages of
earlier publication of the Finance Bill is that taxpayers and their advisers
will in most cases be aware of the precise form of tax changes long before
the date at which they take effect.
That points to good intentions on the government's part; and it is a
commitment that will be welcomed by fiscal policy buffs and the professional
tax advisory community.
The process whereby a appallingly complex measures such as capital gains tax
are sprung on the electorate without careful preliminary analysis, and then
reformed through an expensive process of trial and error in successive
Finance Acts, might just be over.
That would complete a process that started after former chancellor Mr Nigel
Lawson threatened to scrap tax relief for pension contributions. The
resulting howl of anguish from the powerful pensions lobby prompted a rapid
retreat by Mr Lawson. The outcome was an assurance in the 1985 budget that
complex issues such as the taxation of pensions and the structure of income
tax would be set out in green papers before firm proposals were announced by
the government of the day.
The two stage budgetary process does not have deep historic roots. It dates
from the late 1960s, when the Plowden Report's recommendations on a revised
system of planning public expenditure argued for making allocations to
individual spending authorities well before the start of the financial year.
Since governments continued to present their main tax proposals close to the
beginning of the tax year, a gap opened up.
The Autumn Statement was then introduced in 1982, partly in response to the
Armstrong committee's strictures on the schizophrenic nature of the
resulting budgetary process. Since then the government has tended to publish
earlier and more detailed information on public spending plans. Though
widely welcomed, this tended to accentuate the two-stage nature of the
budgetary timetable.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
