<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Income Distribution): Tory legacy of gains in
disposable income - Tax and Benefit Changes Since 1987
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Many of the most radical changes to the tax and social security system
implemented by the Conservative government during its 13 years in power have
occurred during the current parliament.
Since 1987 the top rate of income tax has fallen from 60 per cent to 40 per
cent and the basic rate from 27 per cent to 25 per cent. In 1990 the joint
taxation of husband and wife was replaced by a system of independent
taxation. National insurance contributions have been reformed and reduced.
VAT has risen from 15 per cent to 17.5 per cent. Domestic rates have been
replaced by the community charge. On the benefit side, the social security
reforms of 1988 were presented as the most far-reaching supplementary
benefit, family credit replaced family income supplement, while housing
benefit was reformed and its scope reduced.
Given such an array of changes it is extraordinarily difficult to gain a
clear idea of what their combined effect has been. Hence we use the IFS Tax
and Benefit Model to assess that impact. The model is a computer program
which uses a large dataset containing information on 7,000 households
representative of the population as a whole. Given this information, the
model allows a comparison to be made between the effects of any two tax and
benefit systems on the population. Here we compare the effect of the system
as it stood in April 1987 with that which followed the 1991 Budget. (We
include in the latter system the child benefit increases which occurred in
October of 1991). The systems are made comparable by uprating the benefit
rates and allowances of the 1987 system by the RPI to 1991 prices.
The two figures show the results of this comparison. Figure 3 shows the
proportions of households of particular types gaining and losing, along with
the average gain/loss among households of these types. Households are
divided according to the age of the head, their employment status, marital
status, and the number of children.
Thus, we have classified all households headed by somebody over state
pensionable age as pensioners, any others not in work are placed in the
non-working categories, which thus include groups such as students and the
disabled, not just the unemployed. The other categories are
self-explanatory, except that all households containing more than one family
(as defined for benefit purposes) are lumped together in multiple family
household categories.
Overall, 62 per cent of the population gained from the changes, 27 per cent
lost, and 11 per cent were unaffected (affected by less than Pounds 1 per
week either way). However, the distribution of gainers and losers by family
type is uneven. Only 6 per cent of two-earner couples without children lost
from the changes, with 87 per cent gaining, while 63 per cent of the single
out of work lost and 31 per cent gained. More pensioners gained than lost,
with married pensioners doing rather better than single pensioners.
The proportion gaining and losing is reflected to some extent in the average
gains/losses by household type. Remember, though, that average gains or
losses can be greatly influenced by a few people gaining or losing a large
amount. The average gain for the population is about Pounds 350 per year,
with the biggest gains amoung two-earner couples, but small net losses among
some of those not in work.
Before commenting further on these figures it is useful also to look at the
results by income range. The combination of information allows a better
explanation of what has actually happened. Figure 4 shows the same results
as before but by gross income rather than by family type. The income measure
we use is total income before state benefits have been received or taxes
have been paid. Hence a large proportion of our sample is in the under
Pounds 500 per year category, these being people  - largely pensioners and
the unemployed - whose only source of income is social security.
The results are quite striking. The poorest group lost an average of Pounds
150 per year as a result of changes over the period, with about two-thirds
of the group losing and only about one fifth gaining. As original income
increases, both the proportion of gainers and the size of average gains
increase. Indeed, only in our lowest income group are there more losers than
gainers, and average gains of Pounds 50 per year start in the Pounds
2,600-Pounds 5,200 range. The population average gain is not reached until
the Pounds 15,600-Pounds 20,800 per week range is reached. Of the small
group with incomes of more than Pounds 50,000 a year, more than 95 per cent
are gaining, with an average gain of about Pounds 7,000 a year.
These results are clearly consistent with those derived by family type,
where we saw the poorest groups - the unemployed and pensioners - doing
badly and the richest groups, those in work, doing best. The single most
important reason for the gains among the employed and the rich has been the
reduction in income tax, with the biggest gains accruing to higher rate
taxpayers. They enjoyed the maximum gain from the 2 per cent fall in the
basic rate of tax as well as benefiting from the abolition of tax rates over
40 per cent. Most people in employment also benefited from the reforms to
the National Insurance system implemented in the 1989 Budget. These had the
effect that employees no longer had to pay their full rate of national
insurance on earnings under the lower earnings limit, but rather a lower
rate of 2 per cent.
One other important reform to the income tax system - the change to
independent taxation - affected relatively few people, but the impact on
some of those who were affected was considerable. Among single-earner
couples those where just the wife was working lost from the change as the
total level of allowances for this group fell by the amount of a single
personal allowance. On the other hand, where the wife had a significant
amount of unearned income there were gains. Under the old system of joint
taxation the investment income of a married woman was taxed as if it
belonged to her husband. Under independent taxation married women can use
their own personal tax allowance to set against both earned and unearned
income.
As the charts make clear there were some losers both among the employed and
those on high incomes. These resulted largely from the increase in VAT in
last year's Budget, but also reflect the restriction of mortgage interest
relief to the basic rate and the continuing fall in the real value of the
ceiling for mortgage interest relief, which has remained at Pounds 30,000
since 1983.
Some poorer employees will also have lost out as a result of the reforms to
the housing benefit system which reduced its generosity. This change was
even more important to pensioners, who were the biggest losers from the
reform. In particular many fell foul of the newly imposed capital limit.
Housing benefit entitlement is now reduced for anybody with savings of more
than Pounds 8,000 and stopped entirely for those with more than Pounds
16,000 in savings. The fact that pensioner couples did better than single
pensioners is a straightforward reflection of the higher average incomes of
married pensioners who were thus more likely to gain from income tax cuts
and less likely to lose from housing benefit changes.
Overall the groups with the largest average loss and most losers were the
single without work and those with little or no non-state income generally.
Among the single people not in work two groups did particularly badly from
policy changes over the period. The first were single unemployed under the
age of 25 living away from the parental home and dependent on supplementary
benefit, now income support. The new income support benefit has a special
low rate for under 25-year-olds, and so the transition from supplementary
benefit to income support led to a straightforward fall in the income of
this group. Second, students have suffered very large falls in their
entitlements to state benefits recently. In particular most students are no
longer entitled to claim income support or housing benefit at all, leading
in some cases to quite substantial losses.
In 1988 social security reforms were specifically intended to target more
help on poor families with children both through the income support and
family credit benefits. This shows up in our figures to some extent. While
most non-working couples without children lost over the period, rather fewer
than half of those with children lost. Among single parents there were some
quite substantial gainers leading to a gain on average despite nearly half
losing some income. Finally, among single earner couples those with children
did rather better than those without, partly as a result of the introduction
of family credit which is considerably more generous than the old family
income support.
Other changes brought in with the 1988 reforms which affected many on income
support were the ending of 100 per cent rebates for rates payments and the
ending of the automatic payment of water rates. Though the benefits were
intended to be at such a level as to compensate people on average for this
change many were effectively not compensated in full. This change in the
benefit regime in fact, had a greater impact on those with very low incomes
than did the actual change from rates to the community charge.
Overall, the effect of tax and benefit changes since 1987 has been to
increase the disposable income of more than 60 per cent of the population
and reduce that of about a quarter of households. But the losses are
concentrated in the lower reaches of the income distribution and among those
not in work. The benefit reforms are largely responsible for this. On the
other hand, those in work or in the middle and higher income ranges have
seen gains on average. The biggest gains are concentrated among the richest.
These gains are a direct effect of income tax and national insurance
reductions.
Articles and charts prepared for the FT by Steven Webb and Paul Johnson of
the Institute for Fiscal Studies
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
