FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (News): Business leaders see big reductions in
costs - Northern Response
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN business leaders last night forecast substantial reductions in
costs, better cashflow and an easing of administrative burdens in the wake
of the Budget.
There was a wide welcome for the speeding of the transitional arrangements
for the uniform business rate (UBR) in the north and Midlands. Sir Ian
Wrigglesworth, northern region CBI vice-chairman, said news that the
deferred reliefs are now to be activated would be welcomed by many northern
companies.
North-west business expects the overall gain from UBR changes eventually to
be worth Pounds 310m over the 1990-94 period.
Sheffield manufacturers expect a 40 per cent fall in business rates over the
next two years.
Mr Simon Sperryn, chief executive of the Manchester chamber, said that by
protecting southern businesses while breaking the link with northern
reductions, 'the Treasury will now pay for the change, as we have urged all
along'.
Mr John Hambidge, director of Sheffield Chamber of Commerce and Industry
said: 'There appears to be a much greater incentive and ability to both
listen and hear in an election year.'
Mr Keith Robinson, director of Liverpool Chamber of Commerce, particularly
welcomed help for the car industry because its membership includes Ford at
Halewood, Vauxhall at Ellesmere Port and Delco Electronics, the General
Motors component maker, at Kirkby.
Like Mr Hambidge, he wanted car tax abolished. 'But half a loaf is better
than none at all, and we'll settle for 5 per cent for now,' he added.
In Leeds, Mr Peter Coles-Johnson, an economist who is secretary of the
combined Yorkshire and Humberside chambers, said there would be widespread
relief that Mr Lamont had not gone for 'a fiscal binge.'
But he warned that ending the recession quickly depended on interest rate
cuts.
All the organisations said the introduction of one Budget statement on tax
and spending a year would ease uncertainty in business planning.
Mr Andrew Toop, of the north-west CBI regional council, said speeding
payment of debts was also fair. 'It's a matter of everyone playing by the
same rules,' he said.
The change in inheritance tax is also going to have a widespread impact.
'About 80 per cent of members are small family businesses,' Mr Robinson
added.
Mr Harry Tuley, managing director of the Scapa textile engineering group and
chairman of the north-west CBI regional council, regretted that more had not
been done to stimulate investment in plant, machinery, education and
training.
He said Mr Lamont's prudence was welcome and small firms would find much
encouragement. Personal tax changes would reassure consumers, whose lack of
confidence had had so much impact on the High Street.
</TEXT>
