<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget: Investors shocked by PSBR forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS and City analysts were shocked by the government's forecast that
public borrowing in the next fiscal year would rise to Pounds 28bn.
Prices in the gilt-edged or government bond market fell sharply as investors
recognised that the government would have to sell an increased volume of
gilts to finance the borrowing requirement. Immediately after the
chancellor's speech, gilt prices fell by about 5/8 .
Sterling also lost the modest gains it made during the day, and analysts
said the chances of a cut in base rates were much reduced. The pound closed
in New York last night at DM2.8691, at the bottom end of its range within
the Exchange Rate Mechanism.
Mr Nick Parsons, treasury adviser at Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce,
said: 'I don't see sterling going up very much in the short term.'
'The PSBR was right at the top end of City expectations,' said Mr Gerrard
Lyons, economist at Daichi Kangyo, the Japanese bank. He said the sharp rise
in PSBR showed the 'sheer scale of the recession', which has reduced
government revenues.
In the previous Budget the government forecast revenues of Pounds 240bn for
1992-93. However, the chancellor yesterday cut this forecast to Pounds
229.8bn. Mr Lyons said that the delay in economic recovery meant that
companies and individuals would earn less than expected and thus pay less in
taxes.
However, some investors and fund managers feared that the PSBR may turn out
to be even higher than the forecast: 'I am anxious that the PSBR is
understated by too rosy a forecast of economic growth by the end of this
year', said a manager in charge of one of the biggest UK investment funds.
Mr Brian Pearce, chief economist at the Ernst &amp; Young Item Club, a
forecasting body which uses the Treasury's economic model, said the
government's borrowing predictions 'showed realism' about the poor outlook
for the next few months.
Mr Lyons warned that 'government expenditure may be out of control'. He said
that the government may have to pay more in benefits to the unemployed than
it currently expected.
There were mixed reactions from the chairmen of big City companies and from
fund managers. Sir John Cuckney, chairman of Royal Insurance, and of 3i, the
UK's biggest provider of long-term finance to small and medium-sized
companies, said: 'The economy is like a man who needs a stiff drink. The
Budget was a single, but I think it needed a double.'
Mr Roger Bartley, chief investment officer at County Natwest Investment
Management, said his one concern, a 'personal view', was whether the Budget
was over-cautious: 'The tax cut was of assistance to those (the low-paid)
who would not normally have voted Tory anyway. That might not have been the
best use of money to gain votes.'
Sir Nicholas Goodison, chairman of TSB Group and of the British Bankers
Association, praised the government for not cutting taxes further to buy
votes: 'I am glad they are taking a long-term view.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
