<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Letter: Effect of circulars on share prices need not create
inefficient market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAVID DAMANT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Andrew Jack's article on the effect on share prices produced by
circulars commenting merely on the rearrangement of accounting information
could have carried the argument further. Mr Jack says, the effects in
question were dissipated fairly shortly, so there would only be an
inefficiency in the market if it were possible to make money by buying or
selling after ascertaining that each circular contained no new information
(or judgment about the company in question). If money cannot be made (over a
reasonable number of cases), or if the return does not compensate for the
risks run (essentially betting against the market makers), then there is no
inefficiency.
But if there is an inefficiency (that is, money can be made at acceptable
risk) it does not mean that the efficient market theory is wrong, only that
markets are not 100 per cent efficient: the approach of Modern Portfolio
Theory is now concentrating largely on the fact that there are
inefficiencies to be exploited. Overall, however, the evidence is that
markets (at least in larger shares) are highly efficient at allocating
capital and that mis-pricing is relatively small.
Since the efficient market theory is not intuitive and not accepted in some
important places, it is essential to emphasise that this (possible)
inefficiency does not upset the present state of this theory. Also if there
is this particular inefficiency and it persists, then arbitrageurs will come
in and eliminate it, and fairly soon. Anyway, Mr Jack's article has drawn it
to their attention.
David D Damant,
Map Securities,
2-3 Philpot Lane,
London EC3M 8AQ
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
