<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Solicitor to head Serious Fraud Office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GEORGE STAPLE is to succeed Mrs Barbara Mills QC as director of the
Serious Fraud Office. Mrs Mills has been appointed director of public
prosecutions after only 16 months at the head of the SFO.
Mr Staple, a partner in Clifford Chance, the UK's largest law firm, is
largely unknown outside City legal circles and was a surprise choice to
spearhead the fight against fraud and white-collar crime. But those who know
him well say he has just the right mix of practical, City and managerial
experience for the job.
Mr William Park, a senior partner at law firm Linklaters &amp; Paines, said Mr
Staple had long experience of company and commercial practice, including
civil fraud litigation. Mr Staple worked as a Department of Trade and
Industry inspector in the Consolidated Gold Fields inquiry in 1986 and the
1988 inquiry into Aldermanbury Trust.
Mr Park said Mr Staple's City perspective was probably better than that of
his two predecessors at the SFO. Coming from a different culture, he might
well have a greater awareness of the real evils in City fraud and its
effects on the public.
Mr John Clitheroe of Kingsley Napley, a leading defence solicitor, said it
was a very imaginative appointment. He hoped Mr Staple could 'work towards
an assimilation of the DTI and SFO investigations'.
Although Mr Staple has spent most of his time at Clifford Chance doing
commercial litigation since he qualified as a solicitor in 1964, Mr Nigel
Fox Bassett, the firm's senior partner, said he had considerable experience
of fraud and white-collar crime in the UK and abroad during a period in the
firm's Hong Kong office. Mr Staple is chairman of the authorisation and
disciplinary appeal tribunal of the Securities and Futures Association and
acts as a legal assessor on the disciplinary committee of the Stock
Exchange.
Mr Gareth Williams QC, chairman of the Bar, welcomed his appointment and
said the Bar was not disappointed that a solicitor rather than a barrister
had been selected.
Mr Rodger Pannone, whose firm defended Mr Ernest Saunders, the former
Guinness chairman, and will be acting for Mr Asil Nadir, former chairman of
Polly Peck International who faces criminal charges, described the choice of
Mr Staple, a colleague on the Law Society council, as 'inspired'. Mr Pannone
described him as 'a man of great ability, fiscal knowledge and breadth of
vision, with tremendous experience of commercial litigation at the highest
level.' He added: 'He's also an extremely likeable individual.'
Mr Staple has been on the society's governing council since 1986.
</TEXT>
