<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Managers to take BT to tribunal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of BT managers who claim they have been threatened with a pay freeze
unless they sign personal contracts are to take their case to an industrial
tribunal.
The 49 managers, members of the STE telecommunications managers' union, say
they are among 170 staff who were told they would not receive a pay rise if
they retained terms and conditions negotiated by the STE.
The union argues that BT's action is, under the terms of the 1978 Employment
Protection Act, designed to prevent or deter membership of an independent
trade union.
BT first offered personal contracts to 4,000 middle managers in 1989 and
fewer than 200 now remain on terms and conditions negotiated by the STE. The
union claims many signed 'following pressure and threats that their careers
would suffer'.
BT said yesterday that the tribunal applications were misguided and that it
had never been 'the company's purpose to deter or penalise people for being
trade union members'.
</TEXT>
