FT  11 MAR 92 / CBI rejects plans for Scotland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry in Scotland, which last month said it
wanted improvements in the way in which Scotland is governed, has decided it
likes none of the proposals from political parties for constitutional change
north of the border.
Mr Alasdair MacCallum, chairman of the CBI in Scotland, said there was 'no
evidence to suggest that the proposed alternatives for governing Scotland
offer any improvement in the stability and confidence which are necessary to
improve the indigenous industrial base'.
Neither independence nor devolution would 'stimulate Scottish companies to
compete on price and quality in international markets or to secure higher
levels of inward investment', Mr MacCallum added. The aims of Scottish
business were likely to be best achieved by 'an improvement in the current
administrative arrangements within the UK'.
Mr McCallum said after a meeting of the council of the CBI in Scotland last
month that constitutional change was inevitable.
Last night Mr David MacLehose, the CBI's Scottish director, said
administrative improvements favoured by the the CBI included a single tier
of local government.
