<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Number of share owners falls 1.2m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of personal shareholders in the UK has fallen by 1.2m in the past
year, Richard Waters writes.
This is the first decline since the boom in share ownership created by the
privatisations of the 1980s. About 9.8m people now own shares, compared with
11m a year ago, according to the Treasury's annual survey of share ownership
conducted with ProShare, the wider share-ownership group.
The number has fallen in spite of the privatisations in the past 12 months
of the electricity generating companies and Scottish electricity companies,
and the sale of a substantial stake in BT. It means the proportion of adults
in the UK owning shares has fallen from 25 per cent last year to 22 per cent
this year.
According to the survey, conducted by NOP, 14 per cent of adults in Britain
own privatisation shares, the same proportion as last year. The proportion
of adults owning shares in the companies for which they work has remained
stable at 4 per cent.
</TEXT>
