<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / MoD secures cost cuts in multinational arms project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN has negotiated changes in a joint project with France and Germany
for a new anti-tank weapon fired by helicopters after objecting to the cost
of UK participation.
The decision to remain in the long-range Trigat project was announced by Mr
Kenneth Carlisle, junior defence minister, and greeted with relief by
British Aerospace, the main UK partner. It came a week after the company's
Dynamics guided-weapons division secured a crucial Pounds 570m order to
supply a new air-combat missile for the RAF.
Mr David Laybourn, the division's managing director, said Trigat promised to
provide 'major production opportunities' in the mid 1990s.
The Ministry of Defence said details of the agreement were confidential, but
savings had been achieved by cutting test firings by using more simulation.
Almost two thirds of the estimated Pounds 750m development cost has been
committed. The new plan is expected to reduce the cost to the UK of carrying
out the remaining development work by about half to Pounds 45m over the next
five years.
The decision maintains intact a three-nation programme agreed in 1988
covering both this long-range weapon and a medium-range weapon carried
either by troops or on vehicles. Each partner undertook a third of the work.
It is the only collaborative weapon development programme involving the UK
with both the French and Germans.
UK withdrawal from the longer-range weapon was mooted a year ago by Sir
Peter Levene, then chief of defence procurement. He also proposed that the
UK and France should pursue the medium-range weapon on their own, but this
was flatly rejected by Paris and Bonn. An option is being retained to mount
the longer-range weapon on special vehicles with folding masts, but priority
is being given to the helicopter role.
France and Germany intend to use the Trigat weapon on their new Tiger attack
helicopter. This craft may interest the British Army, but it will have to
compete against the US Apache helicopter proposed by the pairing of
McDonnell Douglas of the US and Westland of the UK.
BAe has reached preliminary agreement to act as prime contractor for the
Tiger bid.
</TEXT>
