<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / North Sea oil industry adapts to shifting tides: David
Lascelles on how low prices and the Piper Alpha disaster have led companies
to change strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE handsome granite homes of Aberdeen with their well-tended gardens
suggest that Europe's oil capital remains prosperous. Yet there are signs of
anxiety in the large industrial estates which house the UK's offshore oil
industry.
The combination of a weak oil price and plenty of spare capacity in drilling
and contracting has led to belt-tightening and close questioning of the
industry's prospects. In addition, changes recommended in the Cullen Report
on North Sea safety, following the 1988 Piper Alpha disaster in which 167
workers died, will add substantially to the industry's costs.
Mr Norman Chambers, chief executive of Rockwater, one of the leading
underwater engineering contractors, predicts that demand in his sector of
the North Sea services industry will begin to tail off next year, the exact
rate depending on the oil price.
'The whole contracting and fabricating industry must downsize,' he warns.
'We're bullish for our own company, but we've got to be realistic about it.'
His views are echoed by Mr Gavin Strachan, marketing and contracts manager
of Atlantic Drilling, an independent drilling contractor. He points out that
at present rigs are used to 78 per cent capacity, compared with more than 90
per cent needed to sustain a healthy market. This has caused daily charge
rates to drop by half to about Pounds 12,000.
'Last year, for the first time, there were more rigs available in the North
Sea than in the Gulf of Mexico,' he says.
Operators blame the softening of the market - at the moment it is nothing
more dramatic than that - on two things: the low oil price which is blunting
incentive to explore, and the widespread feeling that all the big North Sea
finds have been made.
The fact that most current developments are much smaller than in the glory
days of the 1970s and early 1980s also makes them much easier for operators
to stop and start, adding uncertainty to the market.
The industry had made improvements ahead of the Cullen recommendations, but
the new rules, to be phased in from the end of this year, will add a further
burden. The safety modifications might cost an average of Pounds 1m a rig,
says Mr John Archibald, Atlantic's deputy general manager.
The outlook is not totally gloomy, however. A fresh round of exploration
licences has been announced, including 'frontier regions' - areas of the
North Sea and its western approaches that have not yet been explored.
The softening of the market has also encouraged the offshore contracting
industry to think afresh about its long-term future.
The oil and gas group of Scottish Enterprise, the state-funded development
body, has decided that the time has come for 'a long-term reorientation of
the industry from the diminishing home market to international markets'.
Last month Mr Crawford Beveridge, SE's chief executive, announced plans for
an export drive aimed at doubling overseas sales by 1996, equivalent to
growth of about Pounds 100m in 1990 money. 'Expansion of our indigenous oil
and gas companies will only ultimately be generated via
internationalisation,' he says.
One element of this drive will be the establishment of a sales office in
Moscow, where SE sees opportunities for Scottish industry to help develop
the oil and gas industry in the former Soviet republics. About Pounds 25m
has been earmarked for the office, spread over several years.
Aberdeen is also the home of a new International Drilling and Downhole
Technology Centre where oil companies can test offshore equipment on a
real-life rig, but in the safer and cheaper surroundings of dry land. Dr
David Curry, managing director, says: 'We shall be developing technology
which can be exported when the oil runs down.'
However, individual companies will have to adjust to tougher conditions in
the meantime.
Mr Chambers of Rockwater predicts that contracting companies will have to
share more of the risk with the oil companies in order to win business. In
certain cases the company is prepared to forego the traditional client
relationship in favour of forming partnerships with oil exploration
companies. Rockwater will do contracting work at cost, and take its profit
in the form of a share of the royalties.
Last week two Glasgow companies, Kvaerner H&amp;G and UIE, entered into similar
arrangements with British Petroleum to develop the Hyde gas field. BP said
partnerships 'are certainly something we are looking at'.
For companies like Atlantic, hope in the future is grounded partly in
controlling costs and partly in the belief that oil companies will be forced
to step up their search for oil.
'Why do we remain in the drilling business?', asks Mr Strachan. The answer
lies in figures which show that available oil reserves are being run down,
but that the exploration potential is still huge. 'The long-term strength of
the business is that we're going to have to find lots more oil,' he says.
</TEXT>
