<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / World Trade News: Gatt report welcomes Ghana trade reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GHANA's trading partners in Gatt yesterday welcomed its 'substantial
progress' in liberalising its economy but urged further reforms, Frances
Williams reports from Geneva.
They acknowledged a more open economy made Ghana more dependent on better
access to foreign markets and a strengthened international trading system,
and thus on a successful end to the Uruguay Round.
A report on Ghana's trade policies by the Gatt secretariat, discussed
yesterday by its governing council, said sweeping reforms since 1983 had
made a highly protectionist economy an outward-looking one. In face of
constraints posed by Ghana's dependence on primary commodities and high
indebtedness, the reforms had succeeded in improving economic efficiency and
reviving the traded-goods sector.
Cocoa still accounts for about half Ghana's export receipts. Half Ghana's
trade is with the EC, which gives preferential access to its cocoa and other
agricultural exports under the Lome Convention. Ghana's reforms have
included several currency devaluations and introduction of a market-based
exchange rate system.
</TEXT>
