<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Poll battle to focus on taxes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BUDGET designed to wrongfoot the Labour party put income tax at the centre
of the most closely fought election since the early 1970s as the opposition
pledged to reverse the tax cuts announced by Mr Norman Lamont.
After initial uncertainty in the aftermath of Mr Lamont's Commons statement,
Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, said Labour would oppose the 20p lower
rate band at the core of the package. His comments came as a survey taken
before the Budget confirmed that Labour would start the election campaign
with a small opinion poll lead.
Senior ministers voiced confidence that the package - a careful political
balancing act designed to steal Labour's most attractive clothes while
deflecting charges of bribery - would enable the Conservatives to regain the
political initiative.
'It is a simple choice . . . do the voters want a Pounds 140-a-year cut in
their tax bill or do they want Labour's high taxes,' one member of the
cabinet said. Mr Lamont sought to reinforce the message with a pledge that a
re-elected Conservative government would eventually cut the basic rate of
income tax to 20p.
Amid disquiet on the right of the Conservative party about a prospective
increase in public borrowing to Pounds 28bn next year, MPs were uncertain
whether the Budget would break the political stalemate of the last six
months.
Mrs Margaret Thatcher, former prime minister, refused to comment on the
Budget but her political allies said she was 'concerned' about the sharp
increase in borrowing.
As the chancellor deflected questions from political journalists at
Westminster about interest rate cuts, there were hopes among Conservative
MPs that the Budget would be quickly followed by a small cut in rates.
Mr Lamont announced an array of other measures - ranging from help for small
businesses and for the motor industry to increased help for low-income
pensioners - designed to win over key groups of voters.
The changes to the uniform business rate are aimed at boosting Conservative
support among small businessmen in southern marginals. The halving of car
tax should benefit the motor industry in the electoral battlegrounds of the
Midlands. Inheritance tax changes are designed to win votes from farmers and
small businessmen.
As Mr Neil Kinnock charged that tax cuts paid for by public borrowing
represented a 'panic-stricken, pre-election political sweetener', there was
private acknowledgment in the shadow cabinet that the Conservative challenge
over tax cuts for the lower paid had left Labour with awkward choices.
The opposition has long advocated the introduction of a reduced-rate tax
band. But if Labour accepts it now it will be unable to sustain its claim of
Conservative electoral bribery with borrowed money.
Mr Smith, who will announce early next week his alternative Budget, said his
priority was to pull the economy out of recession. Mr Kinnock sought to
reinforce the contrast between a long-term commitment to economic revival
and a short-term Conservative 'fix'.
Mr Lamont, however, said that the voters would be presented with a clear
choice between a government committed to cutting taxes, particularly for the
lower paid, while maintaining good public services, and an opposition
committed to pushing up everyone's tax bill.
The Conservatives, fractionally behind in the opinion polls, are relying on
the Budget to push them into the lead by the start of formal campaigning
early next week.
An ICM opinion poll for today's Guardian newspaper puts Labour at 42 per
cent against the Conservatives' 39 per cent and 15 per cent for the Liberal
Democrats.
The prime minister plans to ask the Queen later today to dissolve parliament
from next Monday. Senior ministers said they expected a formal announcement
today, though Downing Street cautioned that there was still a slight chance
it could be delayed until tomorrow.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
