<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Lamont steals Labour's thunder: Surprise package targets low
income voters - Major set to announce April 9 election today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TORIES' bid for a fourth term in office was launched yesterday by Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, with a Budget calculated to steal Labour's
thunder by cutting taxes for the lower-paid.
The measures, introducing a surprise 20 per cent lower band of income tax to
benefit low-income voters, are expected to pave the way for the announcement
today by Mr John Major, the prime minister, of April 9 as the general
election date.
Mr Lamont not only unveiled the lower band of income tax for the first
Pounds 2,000 of taxable income, he also pledged extra help for poorer
pensioners and extended assistance to small businesses and the car industry.
The chancellor said government borrowing would double in 1992-93 to Pounds
28bn, unsettling the City.
Speaking to a packed House of Commons, Mr Lamont set the tone of his tensely
awaited Budget package by adopting another Labour party policy in announcing
that Britain's unique and much-criticised two-part annual budget process
would be scrapped.
Mr Lamont said that from December 1993 the government's Autumn Statement
spending plans and the traditional springtime revenue-raising Budget would
be combined.
But he held back from widely tipped tax moves such as cutting the basic rate
of income tax by 1p from 25p in the pound or raising tax allowances by more
than the rate of inflation.
Mr Lamont limited the overall Budget 'giveaway' to just under Pounds 1.5bn
in 1992-93 by raising tobacco and leaded petrol taxes and vehicle excise
duty by more than the rate of inflation.
The Pounds 1.77bn cost of the new lower income tax band will also be
financed by freezing some tax allowances and drawing on Pounds 680m saved
from the postponement of the abolition of stamp duty on securities
transactions and other tax changes that have been announced since last
year's Budget.
Mr Lamont hailed his second Budget as one 'for the recovery' which built on
the supply side economic reforms of the 1980s. But its immediate impact was
to present an uncomfortable challenge to the Labour benches.
Although the government's income tax reductions concentrated at the lower
end of the earnings scale, Labour last night pledged to reverse the measures
if elected.
The tax cut for the coming 1992-93 financial year was lower than the Pounds
3bn to Pounds 4bn predicted by many commentators. But the chancellor
forecast higher public sector borrowing requirements (PSBR) than the City
had expected for both this financial year and the next.
He estimated the 1991-92 PSBR at Pounds 13.8bn, or 2 1/4 per cent of gross
domestic product, compared with City expectations of about Pounds 12bn, and
the Pounds 7.9bn deficit forecast in his first Budget. For 1992-93, Mr
Lamont forecast a PSBR of Pounds 28.1bn, or 4 1/2 per cent of GDP, against
City expectations of Pounds 25bn and government predictions in last
November's Autumn Statement of about Pounds 19bn. But he stuck to his
commitment of balancing the budget over the economic cycle.
The package provoked a mixed initial reaction on financial markets, with
equities moving higher. However, sterling and gilt-edged securities fell in
value on concern about the high borrowing requirement.
The market reaction suggested that there would be no early fall in interest
rates. But Mr Lamont later indicated to lobby correspondents that he did not
rule out an interest rate cut during the election campaign.
Although such action would be virtually unprecedented, he said it would be
'a matter for me and the Bank of England'.
In his Budget speech, the chancellor painted a picture in which economic
recovery had effectively been postponed for a year. He forecast 1 per cent
growth of GDP this year with growth quickening as the year progresses. The
Treasury now expects GDP to grow by nearly 2 per cent in the 12 months to
the second half of this year, and by 3 per cent in the year to June 1993.
Retail price inflation is expected to fall to 3 3/4 per cent at the end of
this year, and 3 1/4 per cent by mid-1993 from 4 1/4 per cent in the final
quarter of 1991.
However, the chancellor said he was confident that the lower inflation
combined with the interest rate cuts of the past year would help recovery.
The tax cuts would assist this trend.
The income tax changes will leave most taxpayers Pounds 2.64 better off a
week, but benefit the lower paid in particular. A married man or single
parent will have Pounds 138 more to spend a year, irrespective of whether he
or she earns Pounds 8,000 or Pounds 25,000 a year. The higher paid, with
taxable incomes of more than Pounds 23,700, will be Pounds 160 better off.
The government also announced extra help for pensioners on income support of
Pounds 2 a week for a single person, and Pounds 3 for couples, from October.
Mainly to help small businesses, Mr Lamont announced that the uniform
business rate on 900,000 commercial properties would be pegged in real terms
in 1992-93. This and other measures easing the UBR burden will cost Pounds
480m in the coming financial year and Pounds 590m in 1993-94.
The chancellor also announced technical changes to the levying of VAT to aid
businesses, and exempted most business assets from inheritance tax so that
family businesses could be passed on without charge.
Mr Lamont resisted lobbying from organisations such as the Confederation of
British Industry for an increase in investment allowances.
But Mr Lamont announced a series of far-reaching measures to aid the car
industry. He halved the special 10 per cent car tax to 5 per cent from
today, reducing the price of a typical family car by about Pounds 400. He
also proposed to:
Lift restrictions on businesses claiming capital allowances on cars costing
Pounds 12,000 or less.
Allow driving schools, taxi and car-hire firms to recover VAT when they buy
cars.
Consult on plans to move the taxation of company cars to a system based on a
car's price rather than its engine size.
In a move that may encourage a surge in investment the Budget proposes to
end the Business Expansion Scheme at the end of next year.
The odds about the Tories winning the election shortened after the Budget.
Ladbrokes, the bookmaker, is quoting 2-1 on for the Conservatives to win
most seats, compared with 7-4 on before the Budget. Labour's odds eased from
11-8 to 6-4. The Liberal Democrats remain 500-1.
Lex, Page 20
Capital Markets, Page 48
Currencies, Page 51
World Stocks, Page 57
London Stocks, Page 60
