<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Saatchi falls sharply into Pounds 63m loss: Advertising
group reports worse-than-expected decline over 15-month period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAATCHI and Saatchi, the world's second largest advertising and marketing
services company, yesterday reported pre-tax losses of Pounds 63.6m for the
15 months to the end of December 1991; on a 12-month basis the pre-tax loss
was Pounds 58.4m against pre-tax profits of Pounds 35.6m for the year to
September 1990.
The larger-than-expected losses were primarily due to exceptional items
totalling Pounds 54.5m during the last 15 months, including provisions made
for leases on vacant property, as well as costs incurred in closing and
merging several small companies. Severance costs alone amounted to Pounds
20.8m in 1991 (Pounds 9.7m in 1990).
Mr Robert Louis-Dreyfus, chief executive, added that two companies within
the group made 'large losses' in 1991; he declined to say which companies
had performed badly, but it is believed that the group's consultancy
businesses are lagging.
Before consideration for exceptional items, the group made a pre-tax loss of
Pounds 9.1m for the 15 months. Over the 12-month period that loss was Pounds
3.5m. On a 12-month calculation, the group registered underlying declines of
2.3 per cent in revenues to Pounds 739.8m (Pounds 757.6m in 1990) and of 49
per cent in trading profits, to Pounds 20.5m (Pounds 40.2m in 1990).
Mr Louis-Dreyfus said that net debt averaged Pounds 200m in the final
quarter of 1991 and ended the year at Pounds 180m.
The group's trading figures were affected by recession in the US and the UK.
During 1990, the US accounted for a Pounds 22m trading profit, falling to
Pounds 10.2m in 1991; in the UK a 1990 trading profit of Pounds 7.2m
transformed into a trading loss of Pounds 4.3m last year. However, the group
did better in the rest of Europe, increasing trading profits from Pounds
9.4m (1990) to Pounds 14.4m (1991).
Mr Louis-Dreyfus said the group was budgeting for a slight decline in
revenues this year, though he believed that a more stable advertising market
was likely and that 1992 'will mark the start of a sustainable improvement
in operating margins and profitability'.
He added that he did not anticipate any severance costs this year, but that
a three-year phased introduction of an incentive scheme for the 300 most
senior executives would gradually reduce the Pounds 300m salary bill by 1.5
per cent of group revenues, a potential cost reduction of about Pounds 11m
annually.
Outlook, Page 42
