<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Government Statements): Late payment of business
bills to be deterred - Debt Recovery
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE chancellor announced in his Budget a package of measures to help tackle
the problem of late payment experienced by many small firms and to encourage
businesses to adopt the good practice of government departments in making
prompt payment to suppliers.
The government will require large companies to state in their annual report
and accounts how quickly they pay their bills.
Simpler procedures will be introduced for small claims and debt recovery
cases.
Prime contractors of government departments must include a clause in their
sub-contracts committing themselves to pay subcontractors promptly -
ordinarily within 30 days of receipt of a valid invoice.
In addition the Department of Employment will provide up to Pounds 90,000
for three trade associations to run one-year pilot schemes to provide 'late
payment hotlines' for their members.
The chancellor said the government had every sympathy with small companies
who found that their larger debtors were deliberately delaying payment to
boost their own cash flow. Government departments had a good record in
paying their own bills on time and the government hoped the example it had
set would be followed by large companies throughout the private sector.
Company accounts. The government proposes to amend the Companies Act 1985 to
require large companies to state in their annual reports and accounts how
quickly they pay their bills. Subject to the outcome of consultation, the
necessary statutory instrument will be laid later this year. This will
enable prospective suppliers to have an idea of a company's payment
performance and discourage late payment.
Court procedures. Small traders who either sue, or are sued, for debts of
Pounds 1,000 or less will benefit from continuing improvements to the quick,
informal, 'do-it-yourself' small-claims arbitration procedure under which
the loser does not risk being required to pay the winner's legal costs. The
level at which defended debt claims are dealt with under this 'no-costs'
regime has already been doubled from Pounds 500 to Pounds 1,000.
The Lord Chancellor's department has also already consulted on further
proposals (planned to be introduced from July this year) to dispense with
preliminary hearings in all but exceptional cases, so that cases are dealt
with at a single substantive hearing, and changes to court rules to
encourage district judges (formerly county court registrars) to help
unrepresented litigants put their case.
Government contracts. In future, all those successfully negotiating a prime
contract with a government department will be required to commit themselves
by contract to pay their subcontractors promptly. The government expects
that the commitment should ordinarily be to pay the subcontractor within 30
days of receipt of a valid invoice as defined by the contract requirements.
The new procedures will be introduced from April 5, 1992.
Where a prime contractor fails to comply with the provision for making
prompt payment in his subcontract, the subcontractor will have a remedy
through the courts in the normal way.
Where there is evidence that the performance of a prime contractor has been
unsatisfactory for reasons which may include the late payment of a
subcontractor, that will be taken into account by the department in awarding
subsequent contracts.
Late payment hotlines. Trade associations will be invited shortly to tender
to run one-year pilot schemes to provide late-payment support services for
their members in areas where the problem of late payment is thought to be
most serious.
The Department of Employment will provide up to Pounds 90,000 to support
three schemes proposed by trade associations. They will be invited to
suggest what form the late payment support services should take but it is
thought likely that one of the services will be telephone 'hotlines' to give
advice to association members on how to pursue late payers through the
courts.
The usage and effectiveness of the support schemes will be monitored and
experience from the pilots will be made widely available to all trade
associations and other similar small firm support organisations.
Government departments are already required to pay their bills promptly.
Government Accounting, the Treasury's guide to departments on financial and
accounting procedures, requires the timing of payment normally to be
stipulated in contracts and, where there is no such contractual provision or
other understanding or accepted practice governing timing of payment, for
departments to pay within 30 days of receipt of goods or services, or the
presentation of a valid demand for payment, whichever is the later.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
