<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Government Statements): Agents' paying and
collecting systems to be simplified - Tax Collection
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE chancellor proposes in his Budget to change the way in which UK paying
and collecting agents - mainly banks and stockbrokers - account for the tax
which they deduct from payments of foreign dividends and interest.
Under the proposals, agents will be required to account for the tax within
14 days from the end of the month in which it is deducted. The special
remuneration which agents receive from the Inland Revenue will be
discontinued.
The proposals will introduce a simpler system and will speed up receipt of
the tax by the exchequer. And it will bring the treatment of these agents
more into line with others who have similar statutory obligations.
The changes will apply from 1 October 1992.
At present, paying agents are required to make a return to the Inland
Revenue at, or shortly after, the time of payment showing the details of
payments and the amount of tax deducted. Most collecting agents make returns
on a quarterly basis. When these returns are received, an assessment is
issued, the tax on which is due 30 days after its issue.
Under this system, there can be a considerable delay between tax being
deducted by the agent and it being paid over to the exchequer.
Under the proposed system, paying and collecting agents will be required to
pay to the Inland Revenue the tax they have deducted from foreign dividends
and interest within 14 days of the end of the month in which the dividend or
interest is paid. Payment of the tax will not depend on the issue of an
assessment. Interest will be chargeable if the tax is not paid by the end of
the 14-day period.
The returns which agents make to the Inland Revenue will, as at present for
most collecting agents, continue to be made on a quarterly basis. These will
show the details of all payments made in the quarter, the tax deducted and
the tax which has already been accounted for to the Inland Revenue.
The statutory provision for the payment of remuneration to agents will be
repealed. The present level of these payments is 90p per Pounds 1,000 of
income from which tax is deducted. Payments of this sort are not made to
others with responsibility for deducting and accounting for tax. The change
will result in a public expenditure saving of some Pounds 1.6 million a
year.
The proposals will bring the arrangements for foreign dividends and interest
more into line with other deduction at source arrangements eg large
employers accounting for PAYE.
Tax relief for insolvent deposit-takers: The chancellor proposes to allow
tax relief for expenses and unrelieved trading losses against interest
income received during the compulsory liquidation of companies which were
authorised deposit-takers under the Banking Act 1987.
These companies are unable at present to obtain this relief against the
interest income they receive after their trade has ceased; and the income is
therefore taxed more severely than if the trade had continued. The effect of
this relief will be to increase the amount potentially available to repay
depositors and other creditors.
The relief will apply to chargeable periods ending after today.
Income arising from a trade after it has permanently ceased remains taxable,
but certain expenses incurred can be offset against that income. Relief is
also available for losses incurred before cessation. But some income arising
after cessation, such as interest, is taxed differently and without the
benefit of any deduction for expenses and losses.
Under the proposal, that difference will be removed in the case of companies
which are insolvent and being compulsorily wound up by the Courts, but which
were authorised deposit-takers under the Banking Act within the 12 months
before trading ceased.
The relief will be available against all income which arises after cessation
on the assets of the former business and which would, had trading continued,
have been either a trading receipt, such as interest on loan advances, or
income taxed at source against which trading losses brought forward could
have been set.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 39
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-4181</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCKB6ABWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Comment): Limits of the new consensus
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR LAMONT has presented a budget that reflects the new policy consensus, but
possesses a number of clever touches. He has, in the end, bribed the
electorate much less than some hoped and others feared. But the main reason
for his frugality, the UK's rapidly deteriorating fiscal position, should
give all observers pause.
The chancellor has played the ERM game by the book, the result being a
deeper recession than foreseen and a worse fiscal position than the
pessimists feared. All now depends on the reward for this disinflationary
virtue. Without the recovery now forecast by the Treasury, the UK is heading
for a serious fiscal crisis. But, alas for Mr Lamont, even if that recovery
arrives, its benefits may accrue to the opposition.
As recently as November's Autumn Statement, the Treasury forecast growth of
non-oil gross domestic product at minus 2 1/4 per cent in 1991, followed by
plus 2 1/4 per cent in 1992. These figures have now been reduced to minus 2
1/2 per cent and plus  3/4 per cent, respectively. Thereafter, things are
supposed to get better, with growth at 3 per cent in the year to the first
half of 1993 and 3 1/2 per cent thereafter. But this is not the first time
the Treasury has claimed that things would soon improve.
The recession has had one great benefit. Infla-tion has fallen sharply and
will continue to do so. By the end of this year retail price inflation is
expected to be down to 3 3/4 per cent. By 1996-97, the Treasury foresees the
broadest measure of inflation running at Germanic levels of 2 per cent a
year. Along with real GDP growth of 3 1/2 per cent per annum, this would
seem to be the British equivalent of economic nirvana.
Unfortunately, old British problems are likely to experience several
reincarnations before then. With the public sector borrowing requirement
expected to be Pounds 14bn this year (up from the Pounds 10 1/2 bn forecast
in November), the fiscal position is sliding alarmingly.
Next year's PSBR of Pounds 28bn - after the proposed net tax reductions of
only Pounds 1.5bn - is worse than the city consensus. With privatisation
receipts put to one side, the PSBR is forecast to be just under 6 per cent
of GDP in 1992-93. In 1993-94 it will be just as bad, with the improvements
now forecast for subsequent years depending on a sustained period of above
trend economic growth. Even so, the Treasury is no longer forecasting a
return to a zero PSBR within the forecasting horizon.
Should growth prove to be as constrained by ERM membership as some fear, tax
increases are inevitable. That outcome depends on the British consumer, on
the one hand, and the German wage bargainer, on the other. The chancellor
insisted that recovery is dependent on the behaviour of the private sector.
He is right. But the most important private sector is the German and the
institution that will channel its response is the Bundesbank.
Given the fiscal picture, Mr Lamont could do little but be cautious. Even
so, he may not be able to get the interest rate cut he would like. But he
has at least devised changes in the fiscal structure that the Labour Party
cannot readily attack.
Car tax is an anomaly. The chancellor was right to halve it, though still
greater increases in excise duty on petrol would have been an appropriately
green offset. The chancellor's determination to raise excise duties by at
least the rate of inflation - and more for leaded petrol and tobacco - is
also commendable. The Business Expansion Scheme was little more than a
subsidised property play. Its day was past. And the decision to remove the
bias in favour of direct share ownership in PEPs was overdue.
Business hoped for help, which the chancellor decided to give in the form of
further transitional relief on the Uniform Business Rate. Meanwhile, Advance
Corporation Tax remains unmodified, its payers unmollified. But Mr Lam-ont
was right to eliminate the male chauvinism of the married couples allowance
and wise to avoid the politically correct error of introducing a generalised
relief for child care.
The centre piece of the budget, however, is the stealing of Labour's
political clothes. The new 20p lower rate of income tax is what the Labour
party has said it wants, even though it is far from the best way to help the
poor. Should the Labour party commit itself to reversing the reduction, it
will be damaging many of its own supporters - just what Mr Lamont wants. He
presents the new lower rate as an earnest of the intention to move to a new
basic rate of 20p, a point on which Labour will disagree. It is here, on the
choice between Mr Lamont's carefully targeted tax cut and the Labour Party's
proposed expenditure and tax increases that the electoral battle will focus.
This is the Budget of a chancellor constrained by the disinflationary
consensus. Mr Lamont has given the opposition few clear points of attack,
except over the state of economy. Even here the Labour party offers the same
policy. If the budget reflects the new consensus, its economic fruit looks
likely to remain untasty for some time. This budget does nothing to change
that dismal fact.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 30
</PAGE>
</DOC>
