<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Analysis): 'Qualified rapture' from film
industry - Film Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR WILF STEVENSON, director of the British Film Institute, produced a
suitably theatrical response to yesterday's tax concessions for the British
film industry - 'qualified rapture'.
The main concession from Mr Norman Lamont, who has a reputation as a film
buff, will allow production costs to be written off against tax in three
equal annual tranches after production is complete. At the moment costs can
usually only be written off when a film is released and starts to earn
revenues. Sometimes this is as long as two years after production is
completed.
But after more than two years of intensive lobbying the film industry failed
in its main objective - to persuade the government that the costs of a film
should be written off as soon as they are incurred. This was granted for
pre-production costs such as script writing - a small part of a film's
costs.
'I don't know whether (the change in the Budget) is generous enough to have
much impact,' said Mr Larry Chrisfield, head of entertainment and media at
accountants Ernst &amp; Whinney.
Mr Lamont's estimate of the sums involved as a result of the concessions -
Pounds 5m this year and Pounds 15m in 1993-4 - is, Mr Chrisfield believes,
an indication of the significance of the concession. The government may have
been influenced by a confidential meeting last month between Mr Jack
Valenti, the legendary lobbyist for the US film industry, and Mr Francis
Maude, financial secretary to the Treasury.
Mr John Woodward, chief executive of Pact, the producers association, who
was also at the Maude meeting, yesterday described the changes as quite
helpful.
'I think it's a sign that the government does recognise that there is a
British film industry,' Mr Woodward said.
Last year, according to Pact, 15 totally British films were made with a
budget of Pounds 33.4m. There were also a further 20 British productions,
largely made abroad, costing a total of Pounds 82m.
</TEXT>
