<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Analysis): Small blow to the City - Tax on
foreign interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CHANGE to the way the Revenue collects tax on foreign interest and
dividends paid to UK investors removes a small but in some cases important
cashflow advantage for many stockbrokers and banks.
Given the sharp rise in international investment over recent years, and
consequently the greater flow of dividend and interest income across
borders, yesterday's changes will affect large parts of the City - in all,
600 banks and brokers, according to the Revenue.
In future, any financial institution handling foreign dividend or interest
payments will have to deduct and hand overtax to the Revenue within two
weeks of the end of the month when the remittance was made. That replaces a
three-month gap, which had allowed brokers and banks effectively to support
their cashflow out of taxpayers' money.
Taking away the advantage echoes similar recent changes in the VAT
collection system. And in another parallel to the VAT arrangements, the City
is to take on the role of unpaid tax collector: the Pounds 1.6m that the
Revenue has paid financial institutions to collect the tax until now is to
be stopped.
The changes caused some consternation yesterday among stockbrokers -
particularly since the City is still awaiting the removal of stamp duty,
promised in the Budget two years ago. and a move that would lift one of the
biggest costs on investing in shares. The Chancellor yesterday remained
silent on stamp duty, despite hopes in some quarters that he would abolish
the tax immediately, rather than wait till the introduction of Taurus, the
Stock Exchange's proposed paperless share dealing system. The government's
own difficulties in introducing a legal framework for Taurus have
contributed to the delays in the system, leading to calls from the City for
immediate abolition. That plea fell on deaf ears.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 29
</PAGE>
</DOC>
