<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Analysis): Tax help to creditors - BCCI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEPOSITORS in Bank of Credit and Commerce International, which was closed
last summer, will be the main beneficiaries of new tax relief to insolvent
deposit-takers, according to tax advisers.
The relief will benefit all depositors and other creditors of banks and
building societies which have ceased trading and gone into voluntary
liquidation. The timing of the change, though, makes it of particular
relevance to BCCI, by far the largest deposit-taker to fail.
The new relief applies to the interest income earned on loans made by
deposit-takers which have gone into liquidation. Until now, this has been
treated as investment income, and been subjected 33 per cent tax.
Unlike the regular income of other traders in liquidation, it has not been
possible to deduct expenses and earlier trading losses from this interest
income before tax. That difference has now been removed, though the
concession will not apply to income from the proceeds of investments which
have been sold off.
The change should make more money available for distribution by liquidators
of failed deposit-takers. Touche Ross, administrators to BCCI, said
yesterday that it was too early to say what the effect of the change would
be. However, one tax adviser in London said the ability to carry forward
past trading losses to set off against interest income on the bank's loans
should be a significant help to BCCI's creditors.
</TEXT>
