<PROFILE>_AN-CCKB6ABOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (Income Distribution): Middle-bracket households
win - An analysis by The Institute of Fiscal Studies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THE second successive year, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, has
produced a Budget whose distributional consequences are markedly different
from most Conservative Budgets of the 1980s. Whereas the Lawson Budgets of
1986, 1987 and 1988 produced cuts in income tax rates which
disproportionately rewarded the richest taxpayers, Mr Lamont seems to have
gone out of his way to show concern for poorer taxpayers, and, in the case
of the Income Support changes, for those too poor to pay any tax at all.
However, as our distributional analysis shows, the picture is a little more
complicated than first impressions might suggest.
The first chart shows the effect of the Budget measures on the disposable
incomes of households of different types. The comparison is with a Budget
which simply maintained the real value of income tax allowances and excise
duties and left tax rates unchanged. This is the usual basis on which
governments conduct their financial planning.
The first clear result is that the vast majority of households have gained
from this year's Budget measures. About four in five households are net
gainers from the changes, and the average gain for the population as a whole
is some Pounds 80 per year (compared simply with an indexed Budget).
However, it also emerges from our analysis that about one in six households
is worse off as a result of the changes. In particular, losses are most
likely to occur among non-working couples and among single people without a
job. A combination of factors produces losses for these groups.
In the first place, the income tax cut is of no present value to those who
are not paying tax, and so the non-working population below pension age
largely missed out in this year's Budget.
Second, and for the second year running, the married couple's tax allowance
was frozen and so during the coming year its real value will again be eroded
by inflation. This change cost all married couples paying tax at the basic
rate about Pounds 20 per year.
Third, some excise duties, principally those on tobacco, leaded petrol and
on motor vehicles, were raised by more than the rate of inflation. Even the
poorest households pay excise duties, and so when these are raised by more
than inflation, they again lose out. For all of these reasons some of the
poorer families of working age found themselves worse off as a result of
yesterday's announcements.
For the retired population the picture is generally much brighter. Retired
taxpayers will gain from the reduced rate of income tax, while married
pensioners, unlike their working age counterparts, did not see their
personal tax allowances cut. Meanwhile, for the poorest pensioners there
were increases in the rates of Income Support which, though not due until
October, have been included in our analysis.
The combined effect of these changes is to leave more than three-quarters of
married pensioners better off, and almost all single pensioners with a real
increase in income. Indeed, it is single pensioners in particular who do
well since they will often be older and poorer; they stand to make full
gains from the increases to Income Support.
Looking at the employed population there are average gains across the board.
The largest gains go to couples where both partners are working since they
are both able to take advantage of the new reduced rate of income tax, and
this explains why their gains are, on average, substantially larger than
those for single earner couples. The gains for multiple family households
(for example those with a married couple and a grown-up child out at work)
are larger still, again reflecting the fact that the more taxpayers there
are in the household, the larger is the gain from the income tax cut.
A second way of analysing the effects of the Budget measures is to consider
their effect on households with different levels of income. In the second
chart, we show the average gain and the proportions gaining and losing at
different income levels. Since our definition of income includes only
earnings and investment incomes it should be noted that most unemployed
families or pensioners will fall within the poorest categories.
A first surprising feature of our analysis by income range is that the only
group to suffer losses in real terms is the very richest. In order to
understand this result it must be remembered that we are comparing what the
chancellor actually did with a 'do nothing' Budget which simply increases
tax thresholds and allowances in line with inflation.
In fact, as far as higher rate taxpayers are concerned, the chancellor did
worse than nothing. Instead, he actually froze the threshold at which higher
rate tax becomes payable. Thus as earnings increase during the coming year,
more people will find themselves paying higher rate tax than would have been
the case if the chancellor had chosen to index this threshold. This is a
real loss to better-off families, and it is somewhat disingenuous to suggest
that no group faces an increase in their direct tax. If the chancellor is
willing to quote figures for the increase in pensioner incomes during the
1980s after allowing for inflation, then should he not also assess the
effects of his own Budget against an indexed base?
It might, however, be argued that higher-rate taxpayers will gain from the
reduced rate band and this is indeed true. The reduced rate band saves the
vast majority of taxpayers 5 per cent of Pounds 2,000, or Pounds 100 a year.
However, the chancellor cut the higher rate threshold by Pounds 1,100 in
real terms. Since every pound taxed at the higher rate rather than the basic
rate costs a higher rate taxpayer 15p, then an allowance cut of Pounds 1,100
costs such taxpayers Pounds 165 per year. This more than offsets the gains
from the reduced rate band.
When we look further down the income distribution we see that the largest
gains are concentrated among those households with incomes in the Pounds
13,000 to Pounds 31,000 range. How does this sit with the chancellor's
statement that the majority of the gains would go to individuals below
average income?
In fact, the two results are consistent. What our charts show is the incomes
of complete households. Thus where two partners are both out at work, their
incomes are aggregated because they are being classified by household
income. We have already seen that it is households where two or more people
are working who gain most from the Budget and this chart is telling us the
same story.
However, Mr Lamont's claim related not to households but to individuals. It
is indeed true that much of the gain from the income tax change will go to
individuals with below average earnings. All our chart says is that such
individuals are not necessarily living in poor households.
At the very lowest income levels, the proportion of losers, though small, is
larger than for the population as a whole. This is primarily due to the
increases in excise duties, and the people involved are typically working
age people not currently in the labour market who do not benefit from the
tax changes. Conversely, the gainers at very low incomes are pensioners
either currently receiving Income Support or brought on to Income Support by
the increased rates announced yesterday.
Taken together, our results seem to suggest that what we have seen is a
Budget which has given benefits primarily to middle-income households with
small numbers of losers at both extremes of the income distribution.
Given the chancellor's expressed concern for those on low pay, this might
seem a surprising result. However, the introduction of a reduced rate band
is in fact not the best way to help low-paid taxpayers. A person with small
amounts of taxable income would far prefer to pay no tax than a reduced rate
of tax. Though this may seem self-evident, the chancellor has eschewed the
most obvious mechanism for bringing this result about, namely the increasing
of personal tax allowances. Indeed, in the case of the married couple's
allowance he has ensured that, compared with an indexed Budget, more low
earners will be paying income tax than would otherwise have been the case.
With regard to the introduction of a reduced rate band, the chancellor
repeated a claim more often heard from the Labour benches that the starting
rate of tax and National Insurance paid by the low paid is too high.
However, what is presumably of most importance to someone on low pay is not
the amount of tax paid on the last pound of additional income, but rather
the average tax rate on the whole of their income. To float people out of
income tax by over-indexing personal allowances reduces their average and
marginal income tax rate to zero. Instead, the chancellor has reduced their
marginal rate to 20 per cent. Surely the former option would receive the
vote of the low-paid who Mr Lamont was seeking to target?
It is a common fallacy to reason that because the vast majority of taxpayers
face a marginal tax rate of 25 per cent, we do not have a progressive income
tax system. The defining characteristic of a progressive tax system is that
as incomes rise the share of income taken in tax also rises. As we have
noted with regard to the low paid, what matters is not the rate on the
marginal pound but the rate on the whole of income. On this criterion, the
UK income tax system is, in fact, strikingly progressive.
The latest Inland Revenue figures suggest that for a taxpayer with taxable
income below Pounds 5,000 per year, about 4 per cent of income went in tax;
for someone with slightly more than average earnings (Pounds 15,000 to
Pounds 20,000), the share of income taken in tax rises to 16 per cent; and
for the highest earners (those with more than Pounds 40,000 per year), the
share of income taken in tax stands at 30 per cent. Thus the UK does indeed
have a progressive tax system, despite the wide basic rate band.
In fact, what makes the UK tax system progressive is not so much the tax
rates themselves but rather the relatively high level of tax-free personal
allowances. For the same cost as introducing a reduced rate band the
chancellor could have increased personal tax allowances by substantially
more than inflation and in doing so could have taken more than 500,000
people out of income tax altogether. Instead, he chose to lower the starting
rate. In terms of overall tax progressivity this was clearly preferable to a
general reduction in the basic rate of tax, but equally clearly inferior to
a substantial increase in tax-free allowances. The low-paid should be giving
only one-and-a-half cheers to Mr Lamont this morning.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-4190</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCKB6ABNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / The Budget (News): Number of share owners down 1.2m - Shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of personal shareholders in the UK has fallen by 1.2m in the past
year, the first decline since the boom in share ownership created by the
privatisations of the 1980s.
Around 9.8m people currently own shares, down from 11m this time last year,
according to the Treasury's annual survey of share ownership, conducted with
ProShare, the wider share ownership group.
The decline has come about in spite of the privatisations in the last 12
months of the electricity generating companies and Scottish electricity
companies, and the sale of a substantial stake in BT. It means the
proportion of adults in the UK owning shares has fallen from 25 per cent
last year to 22 per cent this year.
The fall-off in share ownership has not been caused by a decline in
privatisation holdings. According to the survey, conducted by NOP, 14 per
cent of adults in Britain own privatisation shares, the same proportion as
last year. Similarly, the proportion of adults owning shares in the
companies where they work has also remained stable, at 4 per cent.
At the same time, there is little evidence in the survey that shareholders
are broadening their investment portfolios. The proportion of investors
owning shares in only one company has fallen by just one percentage point to
53 per cent, while those with two shareholdings has also fallen by one
point, to 19 per cent.
On the other hand, those with four shareholdings or more has risen slightly.
</TEXT>
