<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is little doubt about where the ratings will go tonight: there is
another lorryload of Inspector Morse at 8.00 (ITV) and so far I seem to be
the only person in Britain to have grown tired of this (and every other)
computer-brained, eagle-eyed, all-too-human detective with odd habits.
Tonight's case involves murder among the rich, not one but two. How do they
think up these plots? It will be well made, Oxfordshire will look positively
edible, and tomorrow everyone will say how fantastic John Thaw is. He is, in
fact, a goodish actor who in this series has received a gift for which any
Equity member would get down on his knees every night for a decade.
In Timewatch General Basilio Lami Dozo, a member of the Argentine junta
which made war over the Falklands, speaks out for the first time (8.10
BBC2).
The food faddists are on the march again in Food File, wagging their fingers
and crying woe, warning us that if we don't change our diet pdq we shall all
die. I have news for them: they will die too, but without the fun that we
sybarites have had with our cream, pork crackling, and pot au chocolat (8.30
C4).
</TEXT>
