<DATE>920311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Scottish Enterprise gives Lecs more cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Enterprise, the body at the centre of the network of local
enterprise companies (Lecs) which handle economic development and training
in Scotland outside the Highlands, is cutting its share of the network's
budget for next year and giving proportionately more to the Lecs.
The core body, now called Scottish Enterprise National, is to take Pounds
65.2m, or 14 per cent, of the network's Pounds 462.6m budget. It began last
year with 17 per cent of the budget.
Three of the larger Lecs - Glasgow Development Agency, Lothian and Edinburgh
Enterprise, and Grampian - have had their budgets reduced. Lanarkshire
Development Agency, grappling with the problems of the closure of steel
plants including Ravenscraig, will receive Pounds 50.2m. Glasgow gets Pounds
58.1m. Other Lecs, including Ayrshire, Dunbartonshire and Forth Valley, also
receive increases.
</TEXT>
