</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 92 / Factory-gate prices up 0.4% in February
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ANNUAL rate of core inflation stuck at 4.4 per cent in February after a
higher-than-expected monthly increase. Prices rose by 0.4 per cent in the
month.
Figures issued by the Central Statistical Office yesterday show that in
February the year-on-year rate of increase in the prices of factory goods -
the key rate of core inflation - was the same as in January, which was the
lowest figure since mid 1988.
Although the figures disappointed City expectations of a 0.3 per cent
monthly increase, economists said underlying inflation remained on a
downward trend.
The latest data suggest many manufacturers are avoiding price increases in
an attempt to maintain sales in a climate of fragile demand.
Excluding volatile items such as food, drink and tobacco, the index rose
only 2.8 per cent on the year compared with a 3.1 per cent rise in the year
to January.
The CSO said this figure was the lowest since June 1969, when it was 2.7 per
cent. It compares with a peak of 6.4 per cent in February last year.
However, the cost of raw materials and fuel used by manufacturing industry
jumped by 1.6 per cent between January and February, bringing the annual
rate of increase to 0.5 per cent after a fall of 1.1 per cent in the 12
months to January.
The CSO said the higher-than-expected increase was due mainly to the higher
prices of sheep, lambs and pigs.
It also reflected a stronger US dollar against the pound and other European
currencies.
</TEXT>
