<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SQUEEZE on stock index futures sent the March contract on the FT-SE 100
racing forward, pulling the underlying cash market higher, writes Joel
Kibazo.
The opening level of 2,536 proved to be the low-point of the session, as the
March future contract found sporadic buyers shortly after the opening, with
dealers who had gone 'short' over the weekend trying to cover positions.
That buying gathered momentum around 10am when, combined with orders from
two leading houses, March was squeezed forward to touch 2,552.
The tentative opening on Wall Street initially caused March to relinquish
earlier gains, but its turnround led to a further squeeze in the dying
minutes of the session, with UBS Phillips &amp; Drew reported to be particularly
active.
The March contract closed at 2,574, around 18 points above its estimated
fair value premium to cash, which fell to around 4 for this account.
Turnover remained poor, coming to 4,782 lots.
The traded options market remained dull, with turnover a negligible 17,637.
Volume in the FT-SE 100 index option reached 7,054 lots. Amstrad was the
busiest stock option, trading 2,555 contracts.
</TEXT>
