<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / International Company News: Citibank to merge asset units
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CITIBANK, the US bank, is to combine its asset management businesses into a
new global division - Citibank Global Asset Management  - with total assets
of more than Dollars 55bn, writes Alan Friedman.
The US bank is hiring Mr Neville Bowen, who has served since 1986 as chief
executive of the investment management arm of the London-based Hill Samuel,
as chief executive of the new unit.
The Citibank asset management businesses being brought together include
activities in 31 countries. Around Dollars 20bn of the Dollars 55bn in total
assets comes from individual and private banking clients in the US, while
the institutional portfolio amounts to Dollars 35bn.
Most of the institutional funds under Citibank management are managed from
London, and Mr Bowen is expected to divide his time between London and New
York.
Although Citicorp raised Dollars 102.5m by selling its Citibank Investment
Management unit three years ago, the bank stressed that it remains a player
in the institutional fund management business.
Mr Richard Braddock, Citibank president, said that in merging the activities
into one unit the bank hopes to become 'a formidable force - one of a
handful of truly global investment firms'.
Citibank's investment operations currently include portfolio management,
cash management and a group of mutual funds.
Fleet/Norstar, the New England banking group, is to become a part owner of
the company that operates the NYCE electronic funds transfer network of
automated teller machines.
Fleet/Norstar will join eight other banks in the NYCE system, which is the
largest cash dispenser network in the Northeast.
</TEXT>
