<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / International Company News: Drexel Dollars 1.3bn payout plan
cleared
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE DREXEL Burnham Lambert saga drew to a close yesterday as claimants
against the once high-flying, but now defunct, US investment bank gave their
support to a Dollars 1.3bn 'global settlement plan' and a US judge approved
it.
The aim is to settle the hundreds of civil claims and lawsuits brought
against the investment bank after it filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection in February 1990. Under the scheme, Mr Michael Milken, former
head of Drexel's junk bond department, would contribute another Dollars
500m, while some 200 of his former colleagues would provide Dollars 300m
from their employee partnership interests.
Added to Dollars 100m of insurance money, and the Dollars 400m which Mr
Milken has already paid into a Securities and Exchange Commission
disgorgement fund, this will create a Dollars 1.3bn pool. The money would be
split between the claimants under court and SEC supervision.
Yesterday's approvals came from two federal agencies, the Resolution Trust
Company and the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation. They had brought
multi-billion dollar suits against Drexel and Mr Milken on behalf of failed
savings and loan associations, which had been Drexel customers.
Last week the FDIC appeared to jeopardise the settlement when it said it
could not approve such a plan without more information about the settling
parties.
However, in court yesterday, the agency's representative said the board had
now approved the deal. Officials explained that additional provisions had
been attached to the agreement providing for the release of some further
information, and allowing the agency to withdraw under certain
circumstances.
The Manhattan court also heard that settling claimants included the
California Insurance Commissioner, who had sued over the collapse of
Executive Life, a large Californian life company which was a Drexel
customer. Also included are the class-action suits on behalf of individual
investors.
The 200 former Drexel employees have yet to sign up on their portion of the
deal, and the judge acknowledged that there was some disgruntlement over how
their relative contributions should be calculated. However, employees who do
not back the scheme and choose to continue litigation will lose the right to
immunity from any Drexel-related suits in the future.
Separately, a bankruptcy court judge was expected to approve the Drexel
'reorganisation' plan. This essentially winds up its affairs, leaving only a
small business to manage the least liquid assets.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 30
</PAGE>
