</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRANS World Airlines, the troubled carrier owned by Mr Carl Icahn, yesterday
successfully sought permission from the US bankruptcy courts to sell its
international routes between the US cities of Baltimore and Philadelphia and
London, to USAir, another large US airline, writes Nikki Tait in New York.
The Dollars 50m sale was opposed by the City of St Louis, where TWA has its
main hub, the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation and the TWA pilots union.
The PBGC and the Air Line Pilots Association argued the sale should not go
ahead before a clear business plan for the distressed carrier, which filed
for protection under Chapter 11 of the Bankruptcy Code, was formulated.
But the TWA creditors' committee gave its backing to the deal, subject to
some provisions over how the proceeds could be used.
The USAir deal still requires approval from the Department of
Transportation, although USAir said it hopes to start serving the routes
into Gatwick, in May.
