<TEXT>
CLOSE BROTHERS, the City merchant bank, reported a marginal increase in
pre-tax profits from Pounds 6.21m to Pounds 6.34m for the six months to
January 31, writes David Barchard.
Earnings per share, however, rose by 13 per cent to 11.56p because of a
reduced tax charge following two acquisitions last year.
Mr Rod Kent, managing director, said that most of the profit centres
reported creditable trading performances and the bank had a good performance
by the standards of the rest of the sector.
The group's loan book increased by 4.5 per cent during the half to Pounds
250m. Mr Kent said that bad debts were at very low levels and provisions
were slightly below those of the last six months. The interim dividend is
raised from 2.8p to 3p.
