<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: Outsider in a risky business -
Campaign Profile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FAVOURITE story of Mr Des Wilson, Liberal Democrat campaign director, is
of the night in wartime New Zealand when his father fired a gun mounted in
case of Japanese invasion near the family's seaside home.
Alas, the suspicious ship his father was aiming at was not Japanese and the
town was deprived of vital supplies as the frightened captain fled.
Mr Wilson, who came to England more than 30 years ago, is hoping this week
to launch an onslaught of equal ferocity and panache on the British
political system. Liberal Democrats pray his targeting is a little more
successful.
Extrovert, enthusiastic and excitable, Mr Wilson is not always trusted by
his Liberal Democrat colleagues. He is not elected to parliament or party
and is accountable only to Mr Paddy Ashdown, party leader.
If the campaign is judged a success, Mr Wilson will take the plaudits. If it
fails, he will be the fall-guy.
With his youthful toothy smile looking ever more misplaced on his ruddy
middle-aged face, the fast-talking 51-year-old Mr Wilson almost goes out of
his way to court controversy, flashing his independence within a party more
used to procedural propriety.
'I never read constitutions in a party. I never go on any committees,' he
says. 'To people who have devoted their lives to constitutions, this is
extremely frustrating.'
He is sociable and generous, a tease with a distinctive antipodean twang,
perhaps happiest at a restaurant table after a hard day's politicking,
struggling with his glasses to examine the label on a New Zealand
Chardonnay. But he insists on remaining the outsider, refusing to conform to
'club rules'.
Addressing the Liberal Democrats' spring conference at Glasgow on Saturday,
the electricity generated came almost as much from notoriety as from
familiarity or warmth.
'He has a lot of the lovable rogue about him,' one Liberal Democrat
prospective parliamentary candidate says.
Mr Wilson knows he has yet to recover from the flak he received for his
handling of the Alliance parties' campaign in the 1987 election -
particularly his failure to stop the public and private clashes between the
leaders of the two parties, Dr David Owen and Mr David Steel. His infamy was
exacerbated by his book on the inside story of the election.
Liberal Democrat MPs, most of whom will be seen far less on television
during the campaign than Mr Wilson, are curiously circumspect. 'He is an
excellent campaign director - and you can quote me as saying that,' one said
tersely before changing the subject.
Mr Wilson's greatest asset is his instinctive campaigning zeal. His eclectic
style dates from school days in Oamaru, New Zealand, when he read through
almost the entire stock of the town's public library, picking up an
encyclopaedic knowledge of cricket and rugby and a scratch briefing on
history and politics.
One of six children, his father ran a house-painting company, and his mother
was a nurse. After leaving school, he became a journalist and arrived in
England at 19, lured by the lights of Fleet Street.
The move to professional campaigning was inspired by a 1960s Kennedy-esque
'ask what you can do for your country' righteousness.
He set up Shelter, the charity for the homeless, taking housing to the top
of the political agenda. Subsequently he has campaigned - with notable
victories - for lead-free petrol, against tobacco sales to children, for
freedom of information, and against pollution.
The breathless dynamism with which he throws himself into his work is
legendary. But there is no career plan or sense of direction. Until recently
he spent weekday nights searching for a cheap London hotel to sleep,
returning to his wife in the country only at weekends. He has written a
low-brow novel, Costa del Sol, aimed at airport bookshelves, to satisfy his
impulsiveness. Another novel is in the pipeline.
Most comfortable when in total charge, he refuses to be paid in his current
post. That means he cannot become a party servant - and also saves expense
for a cash-strapped political party. But taking on such responsibility makes
personal unpopularity inevitable, he believes, given his job of targeting
the most winnable seats. 'Every time you say 'no', there is someone else who
thinks you are a dictator beyond belief,' he says.
He refuses to admit to a temper and dismisses suggestions that he is prickly
under pressure, but to say the least he does not suffer fools gladly.
In spite of his impeccable sense of public duty, Mr Wilson is not a detailed
policy man and is far from an intellectual. He is on safest ground with
party representatives when - as on Saturday  - he makes rabble-rousing
speeches with negligible policy content.
Colleagues fear that if he goes much further under the heat of television
lights, carefully prepared policy positions may be wrecked.
So far, however, he has focused on countering charges that a Liberal
Democrat vote is a wasted vote, and on claiming a moral ground for the party
above the negative Labour and Tory clashes, by calling for an overhaul of
the political system.
Mr Wilson has made no predictions of how well his party will fare.
Realistically he can expect little advance on the current total of 22 MPs -
and possibly some losses  - but with a share of the vote of, perhaps, around
20 per cent.
If the outcome is much worse, and Liberal Democrats blame the national
campaign, Mr Wilson will find the retaliation targeted at him.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
