<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: Parties fail to burst through 40%
barrier - Public Opinion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE week the election is likely to be called the two main parties are
neck and neck in the public's estimation, according to the FT's poll of
polls.
After a week in which Labour believes it has neutralised the prospect of any
tax cuts with accusations of Tory economic imprudence, the compilation
suggests it may still take today's Budget to break the poll deadlock.
The latest weighted average, which takes account of the differing sample
sizes of the seven polls covered, puts Labour almost exactly level with the
Tories - with both parties on about 38.6 per cent, while the Liberal
Democrats are just below 18 per cent.
If this were translated into parliamentary seats, the Tories would still be
the largest single party, with 311 MPs.
They would still be short of the 326 needed for an overall majority, but
would be clearly ahead of Labour, on 296. The Liberal Democrats would have
19 seats.
While support for the Tories is almost precisely where it was in last week's
compilation of opinion polls, the Labour party's showing has slipped from
just over 39 per cent. The Liberal Democrats have recorded a further slight
increase.
At present the Liberal Democrats have 22 MPs, while Labour has 230 and the
Tories 367.
</TEXT>
