<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Living Under The Tories: The state gives to those who have .
. . - Budget 92
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOTERS have been living under the Tories for nearly 13 years. But are enough
people really better off than they were in 1979 when Mrs Margaret Thatcher
swept to power? When her successor fires the starting gun the 'feel-good'
factor will play a central role in determining the outcome of the election.
If Mr Major is to win he must persuade the voters to lift their heads above
the current recessionary gloom and conclude that they are better off now
than they have ever been.
In today's Budget speech the chancellor must not only promise lower taxes
and greater prosperity in the future, he must also persuade the voters that
he can deliver on these promises on the basis of his government's record.
So what are the facts? Has this been a good decade to live in Britain; and
who have been the winners and the losers?
The figures on this page provide a simplified snapshot of a far more complex
reality. But it does seem that, on average, British households saw their
disposable incomes rise faster in the 1980s than elsewhere in Europe. Real
household incomes rose by 3 per cent a year, outstripping those in Germany,
France, Italy and Spain. In part this was because the pre-tax incomes of
British workers grew faster. But the UK government has also shifted the tax
system away from taxing income to taxing spending, leaving more money in the
pockets of British workers.
Value added tax has more than doubled to 17.5 per cent since 1979. But the
basic rate of income tax has fallen from 33 per cent to 25 per cent, while
the top tax rate is now 40 per cent for earned and unearned alike. That
compares with 83 per cent and 98 per cent respectively in 1979.
These gains have not been evenly shared. The pre-tax nominal earnings of the
richest 10 per cent of male workers rose by 264 per cent between 1979 and
1991 compared with 162 per cent for the lowest-paid 10 per cent.
Moreover, official unemployment has doubled from 1.3m in 1979 to 2.6m today.
The real living standards of employed people may have risen by 4 per cent
last year, but rising unemployment has also meant that average living
standards of the population as a whole have declined.
Changes to the tax and benefit system have also benefited the rich and not
the poor. The Institute for Fiscal Studies calculates that the top 50 per
cent of households were made better off in real terms in the 11 Tory budgets
between 1979 and 1990, while the poorest half of households lost out. The
average British household is Pounds 11 a week better off in 1991 prices as a
result of tax an benefit changes. The richest 10 per cent have gained Pounds
95 a week while a single unemployed man has lost Pounds 6 a week.
For those still in work, however, the 1980s has been a decade of rising real
incomes, especially for those on high incomes. Politically, the Tories'
calculation must be that the gainers and not the losers will turn the
election in their favour.
Below we show how four families, all of whom earn above-average incomes,
have fared since 1979. For those families the past 12 years have been
unambiguously good.
The highest-earning family is the clear winner. Its real pre-tax income has
risen by 25 per cent since 1979. But the effect of top-rate tax cuts has
been to raise its post-tax income, net of mortgage interest payments, by 103
per cent.
The percentage of this family's income that is taken in direct taxation has
fallen from 47 per cent in 1979 to 38 per cent today.
For our two-earner family, post-tax income has risen by 31 per cent since
1979. The pensioner couple's pre-tax income has risen by a mere 5.1 per
cent. But tax cuts have boosted their real post-tax income by a healthy 18
per cent.
The regional pattern of living-standard gains across Britain are similarly
uneven. The wider the shaded area, the greater the gain in real purchasing
power - the difference between actual pre-tax income and that required to
maintain a fixed living standard.
Average nominal incomes have risen fastest in south-east England, but real
living standards in the 1980s have risen faster in northern England and
Scotland.
The south-east was hit earlier by rising house prices. Living costs have
risen slowest in Scotland, where the house price boom was more moderate.
All of which paints a mixed picture for the Tories. The painful side-effects
of the Lawson boom and the subsequent rise in unemployment have been
concentrated in Tory marginals in the south and Midlands.
Over the past 18 months the sharp fall in southern house prices and in
interest rates has boosted the living standards of employed southerners
relative to the rest of the country. But try telling that to nervous
south-east householders.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
