<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Credit demand by consumers falls further
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WARY consumers paid back more than they borrowed in January, for the sixth
consecutive month as a recovery in spending continued to elude the economy.
Demand for credit shrank in the three months to January when consumers made
a net repayment of Pounds 293m. This compared with a net repayment of Pounds
212m in the three months to October.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday that new credit advanced to
consumers fell from a seasonally adjusted Pounds 4.1bn in December to Pounds
3.9bn in January.
In January, the latest month for which a figure is available, consumers made
a net repayment of Pounds 62m of credit from finance houses, building
societies, and bank credit cards that are part of the Visa or Mastercard
system.
This followed a net repayment of Pounds 197m in December, the highest figure
since December 1976.
The last increase in outstanding credit was in July last year, when
consumers added Pounds 165m to their debts.
Mr Michael Saunders, an economist at Salomon Brothers, said the latest net
repayment of consumer credit highlighted 'the extent to which consumer
spending and thus economic recovery is being inhibited by the combination of
the large debt burden that was accumulated during the late 1980s and
continued high real interest rates'.
In the three months to January new credit advanced to consumers totalled
Pounds 11.7bn, marginally lower than in the three months to October when it
totalled Pounds 11.8bn.
The figures for credit-card debt were slightly more buoyant. The amount of
debt outstanding increased by Pounds 23m compared with a net repayment of
Pounds 33m in December.
In the three months to January the amount of debt outstanding on credit
cards grew by Pounds 34m compared with a net repayment of Pounds 2m in the
previous three months.
</TEXT>
