<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Complaints to adverts watchdog top
10,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPLAINTS to the Advertising Standards Authority, the self-regulatory
watchdog, passed 10,000 for the first time last year, although the number of
advertisements complained about fell to 607 from 628 in 1990, according to
the authority's annual report published yesterday.
Of the 10,610 complaints about press and poster advertisements, 667
concerned Benetton, the Italian clothing company. All the complaints against
Benetton were upheld, forming more than a quarter of the 2,416 complaints
which the authority upheld. The Benetton advertisements which were the
subject of complaints featured a new-born baby, and a white and a black
child depicted as an angel and devil respectively.
The report suggests that spurious claims that products are environmentally
friendly are decreasing. Other findings included:
Timeshare promotion advertising devices 'regrettably grew in popularity'.
Complaints on matters of taste and decency doubled last year, due largely to
Benetton's campaign.
Complaints about the portrayal of women in advertising fell to 373 from 397
in 1990. The increased number of mail-order advertisements for food
supplements and quasi-medicines, claims for which bear little relation to
their effect, was 'the most disturbing growth area'.
Advertising Standards Authority Annual Report 1991. Brook House, 2-16
Torrington Place, London WC1E 7HN. Free.
</TEXT>
