<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Royal Mail seeks to end 'Buggins'
turn' system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL MAIL, the letters arm of the Post Office, wants to scrap its promotion
system for postal workers, which relies on 'Buggins' turn' - advancement
through long service.
Management had originally set a deadline of yesterday for reform of the
rules but has run into union opposition. The UCW postal workers' union says
more than 20 of its branches want to hold ballots for industrial action on
the issue.
'Buggins' turn' is increasingly under siege. From the end of this month
British Rail station workers will be promoted on merit rather than length of
service. RMT, the transport union, has already largely agreed to the changes
at BR.
Candidates for Postman Higher Grade (PHG) jobs take a written test but, if
there is more than one candidate, promotion goes to the applicant with
longest service. PHG workers supervise sorting and earn 15 per cent more
than basic-grade postal workers.
Royal Mail management has argued that the system works against equal
opportunities but the UCW says promotion by seniority prevents favouritism
or prejudice against women and ethnic minorities.
The Equal Opportunities Commission says it is generally against promotion by
seniority because it could, for example, work against women who take career
breaks to care for children. It favours promotion solely on merit.
The union said Royal Mail tried to reform the system last summer. It added
that a circular was issued but was implemented by local managers only in
areas where there are now threats of industrial action.
Royal Mail says that negotiations with the union are 'amicable' and are
aimed at 'codifying the way experience balances against merit'. Experience
would still play a part in selecting PHG workers, described by management as
the 'non-commissioned officers of the sorting-room floor'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
