<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Insurers are 'losing out' in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH insurance industry, traditionally regarded as a world leader, is
losing out in the European market, according to research published by
Datamonitor, a London-based management consultancy.
Barriers to cross-border competition in Europe have been broken down in the
past five years, and leading French, Swiss and German companies have
increased their share of the European market while most UK companies have
made little impact.
Mr Mike Jones, chief executive of the Association of British Insurers,
yesterday said the report ignored a number of initiatives by UK companies on
the Continent in recent years.
Datamonitor says UK companies have chosen to expand in north America and
Australasia. Nevertheless its figures, which cover Europe's 15 largest
insurers, show that UK companies have been unable to increase significantly
their already small shares of Continental markets.
The report adds: 'British presence in emerging insurance markets such as
Spain, Portugal, Italy and Greece is well behind that of its European
competitors.' The research suggests tough regulatory regimes in many
European countries have dissuaded many UK companies from expanding in
continental Europe. Mr Ian Harcus, one of the authors of the report, said:
'UK insurance managers are used to a much freer rein.'
Of the UK's leading insurers, only Commercial Union has made headway. It
earned 32.7 per cent of its European premium income from outside the UK,
although this largely reflected the strength of its Dutch subsidiary Delta
Lloyd, acquired in the early 1970s.
French insurers - whether mainly state-owned such as Union des Assurances de
Paris or mainly privately-owned such as Groupe Victoire - have been in the
forefront of European expansion. Victoire, which bought Germany's
second-biggest company, Colonia, in 1989, now derives nearly 46 per cent of
its European business from outside France. Victoire and UAP increased the
amount of their non-French European business by 107 per cent and 65.8 per
cent respectively between 1986 and 1990.
Europe's biggest insurer, Allianz of Germany, has also expanded aggressively
in Europe. It derives 48.7 per cent of premium income from Europe outside
Germany.
Switzerland's leading insurers, Zurich, which earns 45.8 per cent of its
European income from outside Switzerland, and Winterthur, earning 39.9 per
cent outside the country, are also well placed.
European Insurance. Datamonitor, 106 Baker Street, London W1M 1LA. Pounds
595.
</TEXT>
