<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Environment ideas sought from City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN HUNT, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL institutions must find new ways to finance environmental
improvements for industry and householders, Mr Michael Heseltine, the
environment secretary, told a City audience last night.
He also made clear that the introduction of a carbon tax on fossil fuels,
which contribute to global warming, was still some way off.
He said the environmental performance of British business and industry was
'disappointing' and that the UK was losing the battle for export markets for
environmental equipment.
Mr Heseltine urged an initiative to form a consortium, or two competing
consortia, to provide a comprehensive package of energy-efficient products
and services, finance and advice.
The consortia might consist of financial institutions, energy utilities and
equipment suppliers, offering a 'one-stop quality controlled package' to
householders.
The Department of the Environment said last night this would have an
advantage over competing advice given when householders wish to install
insulation or other energy-saving systems. It would encourage the public to
be more conscious of energy conservation.
Mr Heseltine called for innovative leasing arrangements to help small
companies which find it difficult to meet the capital cost of
pollution-control technology needed to comply with tougher 'green'
regulations.
There was room for a new package, put together by financial institutions and
the suppliers of environmental technology, to help overcome these barriers
to environmental standards and market growth.
Mr Heseltine had in mind a system similar to the one under which aircraft
are leased to airlines over a long period.
On a carbon or energy tax he said the government was not opposed in
principle to measures being proposed by the European Commission provided
they were adopted by the UK's competitors. 'But there is still a great deal
of work to be done before we know exactly what form such a tax might take,'
he said.
</TEXT>
