<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Nuclear Electric forced to halt auction of contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NUCLEAR Electric, the state-owned nuclear power generator, yesterday froze
its latest auction of long-term supply contracts after being criticised by
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity industry regulator, for
squeezing the market.
Prof Littlechild, presenting his annual report, said the generator had
caused difficulties for customers by putting a very high reserve price on
the two auctions it had held.
He said: 'This is a matter of concern. I am therefore monitoring Nuclear
Electric's dealings in the contract markets and will wish to ensure that
there is no undue restriction of contract availability.'
The generator has been offering contracts, mainly to regional electricity
distribution companies, for the 1992-93 period. Fewer than half the
contracts on offer in the first auction were sold because of the high prices
set by Nuclear Electric. High prices in the second auction led to few
additional sales.
Nuclear Electric has also drawn fire from large industrial power users,
which feared it was helping to cause an overall rise in power prices.
Although the group has only a 20 per cent share of the overall power market
it has a strong influence over the contract market. Other generators channel
much output to the domestic market, in which Nuclear Electric does not
compete.
Prof Littlechild said he would discuss with Nuclear Electric more
appropriate ways of selling its contracts. He said the group's licence
should contain similar requirements to those of the other generators about
plant availability.
</TEXT>
