<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Poll war to begin after Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE starting gun for the 1992 general election will be fired moments after
3.30pm today when Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, begins his
much-anticipated Budget statement.
As tension continued to mount at Westminster yesterday, nervous MPs
impatiently awaited an end to the 'phoney war' and the declaration of a
full-blown election campaign.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, is expected to give formal notice of the
ballot at the pre-Budget session of the cabinet today, confirming that he
has opted for a general election on April 9.
An official statement may be delayed until tomorrow or even Thursday. But
there are no longer any residual doubts in the Commons that the chancellor's
words will be the first shot in the closest political struggle since the
1970s.
Rarely has so much been riding on a Budget. Mr Lamont will emerge from a
pre-Budget purdah, in which there has been no sign of recovery from
recession, to face the biggest challenge of his political career.
In recent days, however, the more extravagant expectations of a massive
pre-election giveaway have been replaced by forecasts that the chancellor
will announce a balanced package with a net tax reduction of no more than
Pounds 3bn in 1992-93.
The aim will be to appeal to a cross-section of voters while presenting the
Budget as one for economic recovery. It will also serve as a manifesto for
future tax reforms if the Conservatives win the election.
A 1p cut in the basic rate of income tax from 25p is expected to be at the
heart of Mr Lamont's second Budget. He is also thought to be planning to
increase the thresholds before which income tax takes effect by more than
the statutory 4.5 per cent indexation. This would help the lower paid.
Lowering the basic rate by 1p would cost the Treasury Pounds 1.95bn while
each percentage point increase in all income tax allowances and thresholds
in addition to indexation would cost about Pounds 245m. That means the
chancellor will be looking to recoup revenue elsewhere if, as expected, he
is also to help industry and small businesses.
Downing Street confirmed last night that Mr Major has a longstanding meeting
with the Queen at 6.30pm tomorrow. This had been put back from Tuesday in
order not to clash with the Budget. It is understood, however, that the
meeting could be rescheduled at short notice. A dissolution of Parliament
would not have to be announced until the following day.
Yesterday, financial markets waited calmly for the Budget. Equities
advanced, the FT-SE 100 index closing at 2,550.7, up 17.6, but trading was
subdued.
Sterling stayed at the bottom of the exchange rate mechanism of the European
Monetary System, losing half a pfennig to DM2.8650. But it gained 0.45 cents
to Dollars 1.723, helping to lift the Bank of England's trade weighted
exchange rate index to 90.0 from 89.9 on Friday evening. In New York
sterling closed at Dollars 1.7255 and at DM2.86885.
Budget Special, Page 12
Observer and Mowlam interview, Page 20
Joe Rogaly, Page 21
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
